ood’ lurks beneath ‘The Little Governess’, and how the figure of the changeling inhabits ‘A Suburban Fairy Tale’. Mansfield’s explorations of the conscious and unconscious mind are elucidated through a discussion of Freud’s theory of the uncanny and the unsettling effects of language in Mansfield’s In A German Pension stories. Finally, the term ‘charm’ is revealed as spanning the two extremes of the fantastic and the ordinary which combine in Mansfield’s evocations of the enchantment of domestic interiors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAuden, W. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterworth-McDermott, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Kay Mckenzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Ailsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavison-Pégon, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, A. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimber, Gerri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKimber, Gerri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowe, Gill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, W. Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonnell, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeverow, Vara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrice, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul